Ben Stiller, along with a great cast, make this two-part movie set a must see for everyone.  Adult humor is involved and may not be suitable for children.  The laughs keep coming though.  Ben Stiller is trying to get into his new father-in-laws "circle of trust", but is really bad at it until Ben learns a secret about his future father-in-law.  Later, Ben has his own circle of trust, and his now father-in-law must earn his way in.

I didn't like the 3rd part. So I was glad they had part one and two available as a combo. DVD's are average quality. For the price they are fine. Extra features might as well be non-existent, so don't expect much there. Worth the money.

Love that the DVD is a two in one pack. Nothing to complain about. It didn't skip or anything. It's just a dvd though, so ... I guess that's about all I have to say about it.

How films like these gain such a devoted following is, quite simply, unfathomable to me. Why talented, heralded actors like Dustin Hoffman and Robert DeNiro choose to make films like this is even more unfathomable - Ishtar was Citizen Kane compared to either of these excreble excuses for entertainment. I saw both of these on the recommendation of people I'm close to; it's clear that, though I love them both dearly, their taste in movies and mine are very, very different. I haven't laughed so little since I saw Camille Claudel - but that won't mean much to most of you. Oh, well.

Meet the Parents was fine. Meet the Fockers was a lot of skips- the disc did not have visible scratches but it sure wasn't smooth viewing- a fit of stops and starts. Sure the price is great but I would rather pay more for a little quality control. I would be giving one star but since it was only one disc that had the problem, I upgraded to two stars.
